Lehigh Valley Business






















SunOpta selling off equipment of one of two Lehigh Valley production lines

    	By Stacy Wescoe,
    	July 27, 2017 at 11:45 AM



Photo courtesy of the LVEDC/SunOpta’s aseptic processing and filling line will continue to operate in Upper Macungie Township.


SunOpta Inc., a Toronto-based organic food company, which has operations in Upper Macungie Township, has sold the equipment for one of the two product lines packaged there.
It sold its resealable pouch production equipment for $2 million to Skjodt-Barrett, an Ontario-based food packager.
In a press release, SunOpta said the sale was made in conjunction with its decision to discontinue flexible, resealable pouch products as part of its ongoing strategy, which had it “exiting product lines where the company is not effectively positioned.”
Flexible resealable pouch products accounted for $46 million in revenue in fiscal 2016 and $10 million in the first quarter of 2017 and were part of SunOpta’s healthy snacks platform in its consumer products segment.
SunOpta opened food-pouch manufacturing operations in Upper Macungie in 2012 and added a $25 million expansion in late 2015 to add aseptic processing for soy, almond and similar milk products.
Aseptic processing production will continue at the plant.
The company did not respond to a question on how the equipment sale would affect employment at the facility, although Dave Colo, CEO of SunOpta, issued a statement.
“I want to thank all of our employees involved in the flexible resealable pouch operations for their hard work and dedication,” Colo said. “Each employee has contributed to our goal of bringing well-being to life in their own way and has had a meaningful impact at SunOpta.”
As of February 2016, the company reported adding 48 jobs for aseptic processing on top of the 52 employees it had previously on the resealable pouch production line.
The equipment sale is expected to be completed in the fourth quarter this year.



