Manufacturing 



SunOpta expects to cut about 60 employees in Upper Macungie








SunOpta Inc. / HANDOUT
SunOpta Inc. in 2015 completed a $25 million expansion at its Upper Macungie facility, located at 7108 Daniels Drive.
SunOpta Inc. in 2015 completed a $25 million expansion at its Upper Macungie facility, located at 7108 Daniels Drive. (SunOpta Inc. / HANDOUT)

Jon HarrisContact ReporterOf The Morning Call




Global organic food company SunOpta Inc. expects to reduce employment at its Upper Macungie Township plant by about 60 workers as it exits the flexible, resealable pouch business and attempts a turnaround of its business.SunOpta on Thursday announced it has signed an agreement to sell equipment used in the production of flexible, resealable pouches at its Upper Macungie facility to Ontario-based food company Skjodt-Barrett for $2 million. The equipment sale is expected to close during the fourth quarter.That means the Upper Macungie plant, which employs 114, won’t be a dual-purpose consumer products facility for much longer. While one part of the facility handles flexible, resealable pouches primarily for baby food, SunOpta completed a $25 million expansion in November 2015 that added aseptic processing capabilities for beverages such as soy or almond milk.SunOpta said it will continue to produce aseptic beverages from the Upper Macungie facility. In fact, a spokesman said, SunOpta could expand its aseptic beverage capabilities at the plant. With that in mind, SunOpta said it has no intention of reducing its footprint in the 101,000-square-foot facility at 7108 Daniels Drive.

SunOpta leases the facility from J.G. Petrucci Co. Inc., and the lease doesn’t expire until April 2027, according to the company’s annual report.SunOpta expects to run the pouch business at the plant through October. The roughly 60 employees who will be affected by SunOpta’s decision will be considered for openings on the aseptic side of the plant or at other SunOpta facilities, the company said.“I want to thank all of our employees involved in the flexible resealable pouch operations for their hard work and dedication,” SunOpta CEO Dave Colo said in a news release. “Each employee has contributed to our goal of bringing well-being to life in their own way and has had a meaningful impact at SunOpta.”SunOpta, with its partner Oaktree Capital Management, has been trying to turn the company around through a value-creation plan that focuses on four pillars: portfolio optimization, operational excellence, go-to-market effectiveness and process sustainability.

In the first quarter, SunOpta reported a loss of $11.4 million, or 16 cents a share, compared with a loss in the year-earlier period of $9.7 million, or 11 cents a share. The company also reported revenues of $330 million in the quarter, a 6.3 percent decrease from $352.3 million a year earlier.Colo said the equipment sale  fits into the company’s new strategy and will allow for the redeployment of capital for investment in more profitable parts of SunOpta’s business.The flexible, resealable pouch business and aseptic beverage unit have appeared to be headed in different directions for quite some time. Consider the company’s fourth-quarter results in 2015.While the new aseptic beverage operation in Upper Macungie was just ramping up and starting to win the company new business, SunOpta had to eat $2.2 million in costs because of downtime and spoilage resulting from an equipment failure during the quarter in the pouch side of the local plant.









